   <abstract>Map shows Battle of Franklin where the United States Forces repulsed the Confederate Army on November 30, 1864. Includes topography, roads, disposition of Union works and Confederate forces, houses and landowners, fortified positions, and layout of Town of Franklin. Blueprint version of Map 27 in the TSLA Map Collection.</abstract>
   <abstract>The Battle of Franklin was one of the worst disasters of the Civil War for the Confederate Army. Confederate Lt. Gen. John Bell Hood's Army of Tennessee conducted numerous frontal assaults against Union forces under Maj. Gen. John M. Schofield and was unable to break through. The Confederates ultimately took Franklin, but at great cost, incurring over six thousand casualties including fourteen generals. Though published ten years after the battle, this map contains a wealth of important details and was compiled by Col. William E. Merrill, one of the foremost Union cartographers working in Tennessee during the Civil War.</abstract>
